 {"id":"bd-2ktrc.1","title":"[TESTING] Implement fault injection for message reorder/duplication","description":"Implement fault injection hooks that simulate message reorder and duplication in Asupersync's channel system. This tests that obligation protocols remain correct when messages arrive out of order or are duplicated. Implementation: (1) Add a FaultInjector trait with reorder_probability and duplication_probability parameters, (2) Hook into the channel send path to intercept messages and apply faults, (3) Reorder: buffer N messages and emit in random permutation, (4) Duplication: clone message and deliver twice. Lab runtime integration: faults are deterministic (seeded PRNG) and replayable. Pass criteria: (a) No obligation leak under any fault scenario, (b) Idempotency — duplicated messages do not cause double-processing, (c) Eventual delivery — reordered messages are all eventually delivered. Must log all injected faults to EvidenceLedger for debugging.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T09:19:36.121232506Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T21:27:43.776234279Z","closed_at":"2026-02-13T21:27:09.792959240Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["fault-injection","messages","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.1","depends_on_id":"bd-1e2if.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:30Z","created_by":"import"},{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.1","depends_on_id":"bd-2ktrc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:30Z","created_by":"import"}],"comments":[{"id":1405,"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Implemented FaultSender wrapper + integration tests. 34 tests pass. Commit 9a1dbce.","created_at":"2026-02-13T20:54:42Z"},{"id":1407,"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.1","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Verified and closed. FaultSender wraps mpsc::Sender with deterministic message reorder and duplication. 34 tests covering all 5 pass criteria. Clippy/fmt clean.","created_at":"2026-02-13T21:27:43Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-2ktrc.2","title":"[TESTING] Implement fault injection for network partition","description":"Implement fault injection for simulating network partitions between Asupersync actors and services. Partitions are the most critical fault type — they test whether the saga system correctly detects unreachable participants and triggers compensation. Implementation: (1) Partition model: define which actor pairs can communicate (connectivity graph), (2) Partition injection: block message delivery between partitioned actors, (3) Partition healing: restore connectivity after configurable duration, (4) Partial partition: asymmetric partitions where A can reach B but not vice versa. Lab runtime integration: partitions are scheduled events in virtual time. Pass criteria: (a) Saga compensation triggers correctly under partition, (b) No split-brain — partitioned actors do not make conflicting decisions, (c) Recovery after partition heal — system converges to consistent state, (d) Budget/deadline expiry during partition causes correct cancellation. Must test: 2-way, 3-way, and cascading partitions.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T09:19:45.081462050Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T21:25:26.136115266Z","closed_at":"2026-02-13T21:25:14.568473856Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["fault-injection","partition","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.2","depends_on_id":"bd-1e2if.4","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:30Z","created_by":"import"},{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.2","depends_on_id":"bd-2ktrc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:30Z","created_by":"import"}],"comments":[{"id":1406,"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.2","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Implemented PartitionController + PartitionSender<T> in src/channel/partition.rs. 27 tests (11 unit + 16 integration) covering all 7 pass criteria. Committed as 1db2776.","created_at":"2026-02-13T21:25:26Z"}]}
-{"id":"bd-2ktrc.3","title":"[TESTING] Implement fault injection for crash/restart","description":"Implement fault injection for simulating actor crash and restart in Asupersync. Crash faults test whether the supervision tree correctly detects failed actors, cleans up their obligations, and restarts them. Implementation: (1) Crash injection: kill actor at random point during execution (after N operations or at specific protocol step), (2) Restart model: restart actor with fresh state (cold restart) or from last checkpoint (warm restart), (3) Cascade crash: crash supervisor to test supervision tree recovery. Lab runtime integration: crashes are scheduled events with deterministic timing. Pass criteria: (a) All obligations held by crashed actor are released (no leak), (b) Supervisor detects crash and restarts within configured timeout, (c) Restarted actor resumes from correct protocol state, (d) In-flight messages to crashed actor are properly handled (timeout or redirect), (e) Crash during two-phase commit triggers abort, not partial commit. Must test: single crash, double crash, supervisor crash, crash during cancellation.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T09:19:52.775914435Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T21:51:26.560654387Z","closed_at":"2026-02-13T21:51:14.413249567Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["crash","fault-injection","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.3","depends_on_id":"bd-1e2if.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:23Z","created_by":"import"},{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.3","depends_on_id":"bd-2ktrc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:23Z","created_by":"import"}],"comments":[{"id":1408,"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.3","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Verified and fixed crash/restart fault injection. Fixes: clippy finish_non_exhaustive on CrashController Debug impl, integration test deadlock (100 sends into capacity-16 channel), redundant clone. 16 unit + 21 integration tests all passing, clippy clean, fmt clean. Commit 75c3895.","created_at":"2026-02-13T21:51:26Z"}]}
-{"id":"bd-2ktrc.4","title":"[TESTING] Implement fault injection for clock skew","description":"Implement fault injection for simulating clock skew between Asupersync actors. Clock skew tests whether timeout-based protocols (lease expiry, budget deadlines, heartbeat detection) remain correct when clocks diverge.

BACKGROUND: In distributed systems, clock skew is a fundamental source of bugs. Even with NTP, clocks can diverge by milliseconds (normal) to seconds (pathological). The CALM theorem (Graveyard section 13.3) notes that monotone programs are clock-insensitive, but threshold-based operations (lease expiry, timeout detection) are inherently clock-dependent. Testing with simulated clock skew validates that the system uses causal ordering (logical clocks) rather than wall-clock assumptions for correctness-critical decisions.

RUST IMPLEMENTATION GUIDANCE: (1) Define ClockSkewInjector struct with per_actor_offset: HashMap<ActorId, Duration> for static skew and drift_rate: HashMap<ActorId, f64> for progressive drift (ms/s). (2) Hook into the virtual time system from bd-1hu19.3: each actors VirtualClock applies its offset before returning the current time. (3) Clock jump: schedule a sudden offset change at a specific virtual time point to simulate NTP correction. (4) Monotonicity violation: temporarily return a time earlier than the previous read (detects code that assumes monotonic clocks). (5) Integration with FrankenLab scenario YAML: clock_skew section in fault schedule specifying per-actor offsets, drift rates, and jump events. (6) Use quanta crate for high-resolution clock abstraction that can be swapped for virtual clock in tests.

ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA: (1) Lease expiry is correct despite clock skew -- use causal ordering, not wall-clock, for lease validity determination. Specifically: a lease acquired at logical time T with duration D expires at logical time T+D regardless of wall-clock skew. (2) Budget deadlines account for worst-case skew -- budget remaining calculation uses the maximum clock reading across all participants. (3) Heartbeat detection uses logical clocks -- a heartbeat received with a different wall-clock timestamp is accepted if the logical clock is within bounds. (4) No liveness violation -- system makes progress despite bounded clock skew (verified: all sagas complete within 2x the non-skewed baseline time). (5) Clock jump does not cause spurious lease expiry or budget exhaustion. (6) Monotonicity violation is detected and logged as a warning (system continues, does not crash).

LOGGING REQUIREMENTS: Each clock skew injection emits structured log: actor_id, original_time_ms, skewed_time_ms, offset_ms, drift_rate, event_type (static_offset|drift|jump|monotonicity_violation). All injected faults logged to EvidenceLedger: component=clock_skew_injector, action=skew_applied, top_features includes max_skew_ms, affected_actor_count. Aggregate stats at test completion: max_observed_skew_ms, monotonicity_violations_count, lease_expiry_correctness (pass/fail count).

TESTING APPROACH: (1) Unit tests: verify ClockSkewInjector correctly applies offsets and drift rates. (2) Lease tests: acquire lease under various skew conditions (0ms, 10ms, 100ms, 1s), verify correct expiry. (3) Budget tests: propagate budget through actors with different clock offsets, verify deadline correctness. (4) Heartbeat tests: verify heartbeat detection with skewed clocks. (5) Property tests (proptest): for any bounded clock skew (< 1s), all protocols eventually complete. (6) Integration: run full saga under clock skew via FrankenLab scenario, verify identical outcome to non-skewed execution.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T09:19:59.965023589Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T21:53:28.824509120Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["clock-skew","fault-injection","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.4","depends_on_id":"bd-2ktrc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:43Z","created_by":"import"}]}
-{"id":"bd-2ktrc.5","title":"[TESTING] Loom-based concurrency tests for scheduler queues","description":"Implement Loom-based concurrency tests for Asupersync's scheduler queues and lock-free data structures. Loom exhaustively explores all possible thread interleavings to find concurrency bugs that are nearly impossible to catch with random testing.

BACKGROUND (Tier C Formal Assurance, Graveyard section 0.14): Loom provides model-checked concurrency testing by controlling thread scheduling and exploring all valid interleavings. Unlike stress tests that probabilistically find bugs, loom guarantees that if a bug exists within the exploration bound, it will be found. This corresponds to Tier C (Deductive Verification) on the formal assurance ladder because it provides exhaustive coverage within bounds.

RUST IMPLEMENTATION GUIDANCE: (1) Add loom as a dev-dependency behind a cfg(loom) feature flag. (2) Replace std::sync::atomic with loom::sync::atomic in testable code using conditional imports: #[cfg(loom)] use loom::sync::atomic::AtomicUsize; #[cfg(not(loom))] use std::sync::atomic::AtomicUsize. (3) Create a separate test binary: tests/loom_tests.rs that only runs under cargo test --features loom. (4) Use loom::model(|| { ... }) to wrap each test case. (5) For work-stealing deque: test push/pop from owner thread, steal from multiple thief threads, verify no lost items and no duplicates. (6) For MPSC channel: test concurrent sends from N producers, single consumer recv, verify total ordering within each producer and no message loss. (7) For task state machine: test concurrent wake/cancel/complete transitions, verify exactly one terminal state is reached. (8) For budget counter: test concurrent decrements from N threads, verify counter never goes below zero and final value equals initial minus total decrements.

COVERAGE TARGETS: (1) Work-stealing deque: all push/pop/steal interleavings with 2 threads, 3 operations each. (2) MPSC channel: all send/recv interleavings with 3 senders, 1 receiver, 2 messages each. (3) Task state machine: all wake/cancel/complete interleavings with 2 threads. (4) Budget counter: all decrement/check interleavings with 3 threads, 2 decrements each.

ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA: (1) All loom tests pass with max_preemptions=2 (CI fast mode). (2) All loom tests pass with max_preemptions=4 (nightly thorough mode). (3) No data races detected by loom (loom catches these automatically via its memory model). (4) No deadlocks (all model executions terminate within bounded steps). (5) Correct final state in all explored interleavings. (6) Loom tests complete in < 5 minutes for CI, < 30 minutes for nightly.

LOGGING REQUIREMENTS: Each loom test logs: test_name, max_preemptions, total_interleavings_explored, execution_time_ms, pass_fail. On failure: log the specific interleaving that caused the failure (loom provides a trace of scheduling decisions). Summary at test suite completion: total_tests, total_interleavings, unique_bugs_found. All output in structured JSON for CI parsing.

TESTING APPROACH (meta): (1) Start with the simplest data structure (budget counter) to validate the loom test infrastructure. (2) Progressively add more complex structures. (3) Use loom::thread::yield_now() at critical points to increase exploration coverage. (4) Compare loom results against tokio-test stress tests to validate that loom catches bugs stress tests miss.","status":"open","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-02-13T09:20:09.545514942Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-02-13T17:30:43.157495786Z","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["concurrency","loom","testing"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-2ktrc.5","depends_on_id":"bd-2ktrc","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-02-13T18:30:15Z","created_by":"import"}]}
